title: Excitation functions for the formation of longer lived isotopes by deuteron irradiation of Europium

x4freetext: Excitation functions for the formation of longer
lived isotopes by deuteron irradiation of Europium

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.310, p.54 (2013)

x4codes.hlp: Catholic Univ. of Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium

x4freetext: High purity (99.9%) from
Goodfellow, nominal thickness 120 micro-m.
Natural europium target foils (25 pieces, 10x10 mm)
cut from a larger sheet (Goodfellow, nominal thickness
120 micro-m). The weight and size of the Eu sheet was
measured and an average thickness of Eu target foils
was calculated. One stack was assembled using Eu foils
and Sb sandwich foils (details in D4265 entry),
interleaved with 50 micro-m thick Al foils and
10 micro-m thick Ti foils (Goodfellow, 99.99%) placed
at the low energy segment of the stack, below the
threshold energy of the reactions on the aluminium,
for monitoring the beam energy and intensity.
The assembled target was kept under vacuum until
irradiation. The irradiation took place at an external
beam line of the CGR90 cyclotron in Louvain la Neuve,
Belgium. The initial deuteron energy was set carefully
to 50 MeV. The beam current was kept constant at about
100 nA during the 1.5 h irradiation time.
No chemical separation was applied after irradiation.
Each foil was measured 3 times.

x4freetext: ,  Ti+d
The uncertainty on the median energy in the
foils includes the cumulative effects of uncertainty of
incident beam energy, uncertainty of stopping power of
each foil due to thickness variation and  straggling
effects.
The uncertainty on the cross section values
are estimated in the  standard way following the
recommendations of the ISO-guide as the square root of
the quadratic summation of the independently
contributing parameters. Uncertainty of time parameters
is not included.
surface density of target nuclei(5%),
incident charged particle flux (5%),
nuclear decay and branching data(3%)
detector efficiency (4-9%)
statistical and peak fitting (2-8%)
The experimental data were compared to the
results of the theoretical model codes TENDL-2011.
The measured experimental data were compared to
those found in the literature.
Fitted excitation functions were used for
determination of integral physical yields.
Entry was checked by the corresponding author.
VS. SF4 in subent. 004 corrected.
